<DIV class=3Dweblogdate>
<H1>Tuesday, May 06, 2008</H1><A =
name=3Da381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9e7b></A>
<DIV class=3DweblogEntry>
<DIV class=3DweblogEntryNav><A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/2008/05/06/Rare+Insight+Into+The+IPy+Team.aspx=
">=C2=AB&nbsp;Rare=20
Insight Into the IPy Team</A> | <A =
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/default.aspx"=20
rel=3Dhome>Home</A> | <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/2008/05/07/Deserializing+XML+With+IronPython.a=
spx">Deserializing=20
XML with IronPython&nbsp;=C2=BB</A> </DIV>
<H2><A class=3DTitleLinkStyle=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/2008/05/06/Stream+Processing+XML+In+IronPython=
.aspx"=20
rel=3Dbookmark>Stream Processing XML in IronPython</A></H2>
<P align=3Dleft>When it comes to processing XML, there are two basic =
approaches -=20
load it all into memory at once or process it a node at a time. In the =
.NET=20
world where I have spent most of the past ten years, those two models =
are=20
represented by <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fmsdn.microsoft.com%2flibrary%2fsystem.xml.xmld=
ocument">XmlDocument</A>=20
and <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fmsdn.microsoft.com%2flibrary%2fsystem.xml.xmlr=
eader">XmlReader</A>.=20
There are alternatives to XmlDocument, such as <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fmsdn.microsoft.com%2flibrary%2fsystem.xml.linq=
.xdocument">XDocument</A>=20
and <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fmsdn.microsoft.com%2flibrary%2fsystem.xml.xpat=
h.xpathdocument">XPathDocument</A>,=20
but you get the idea.</P>
<P>Out in non-MSFT land, the same two basic models exist, however the de =
facto=20
standard for stream based processing is SAX, the <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fwww.saxproject.org%2f">Simple=20
API for XML</A>. SAX is supported by <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fwww.saxproject.org%2flangs.html">many=20
languages</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fwww.python.org%2fdoc%2fcurrent%2flib%2fmodule-=
xml.sax.html">including=20
Python</A>.</P>
<P>Personally, I've never been a fan of SAX's event-driven approach. =
Pushing=20
events makes total sense for a human driven UI, but I never understood =
why=20
anyone thought that was a good idea for stream processing XML. I like=20
XmlReader's pull model much better. When you're ready for the next node, =
just=20
call <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fmsdn.microsoft.com%2flibrary%2fsystem.xml.xmlr=
eader.Read">Read</A>()=20
- no mucking about setting <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fwww.saxproject.org%2fapidoc%2forg%2fxml%2fsax%=
2fContentHandler.html">content=20
handlers</A> or handling node processing events. </P>
<P>Luckily, the <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fdocs.python.org%2flib%2flib.html">Python=20
standard library</A> supports both approaches. It provides both a <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fdocs.python.org%2flib%2fmodule-xml.sax.html">S=
AX=20
based parser</A> as well as a <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fdocs.python.org%2flib%2fmodule-xml.dom.pulldom=
.html">pull=20
based parser called pulldom</A>. Pulldom doc's are fairly sparse, but <A =

href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fwww.prescod.net%2f">Paul=20
Prescod</A> wrote a <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fwww.prescod.net%2fpython%2fpulldom.html">nice =

introduction</A>. Here's an example from Paul's site (slightly =
modified):</P>
<DIV style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: consolas,lucida console,courier new"><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">from</SPAN> xml<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
blue">.</SPAN>dom <SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">import</SPAN> pulldom <BR>nodes =3D pulldom<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">.</SPAN>parse<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
blue">(</SPAN>&nbsp;<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: maroon">"file.xml"</SPAN>&nbsp;<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">)</SPAN>&nbsp; <BR><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">for</SPAN>&nbsp;<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">(</SPAN>event,node<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">)</SPAN>&nbsp;<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
blue">in</SPAN> nodes<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">:</SPAN>&nbsp; <BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">if</SPAN> event=3D=3D<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: maroon">"START_ELEMENT"</SPAN>&nbsp;<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">and</SPAN> node<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">.</SPAN>tagName=3D=3D<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: maroon">"table"</SPAN><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
blue">:</SPAN>&nbsp;=20
<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; nodes<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">.</SPAN>expandNode<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
blue">(</SPAN> node=20
<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: blue">)</SPAN></DIV>
<P>Actually, I like this <EM>better</EM> than XmlReader, since it =
provides the=20
nodes in a list-like construct that appeals to the functional programmer =
in me.=20
I'd like it even more if Python had a native pattern matching syntax - =
you know,=20
like F# - but you can get similar results by chaining together =
conditionals with=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fdocs.python.org%2fref%2fif.html">elif</A>.</P>=

<P>However, IronPython doesn't support any of the XML parsing modules =
from=20
Python's standard library. They're all based on a C-based python module =
called=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fdocs.python.org%2flib%2fmodule-xml.parsers.exp=
at.html">pyexpat</A>=20
which IronPython can't load. [1] I wanted a pulldom type model, so I =
decided to=20
wrap XmlReader to provide a similar API and lets me write code like =
this:</P>
<DIV style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: consolas,lucida console,courier new"><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">import</SPAN> ipypulldom&nbsp; <BR>nodes =3D =
ipypulldom<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">.</SPAN>parse<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
blue">(</SPAN>&nbsp;<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: maroon">"sample.xml"</SPAN>&nbsp;<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">for</SPAN> node <SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
blue">in</SPAN>=20
nodes<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: blue">:</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR>&nbsp; <SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">if</SPAN> node<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">.</SPAN>nodeType=3D=3DXmlNodeType<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">.</SPAN>Element<SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">:</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: blue">print</SPAN> node<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
blue">.</SPAN>xname=20
<BR></DIV>
<P>There are a few differences from pulldom, but it's basically the same =
model.=20
I'm using the native .NET type XmlNodeType rather than a string to =
indicate the=20
node type. Furthermore, I made the node type a property of the node, =
rather than=20
a separate variable. I also didn't implement expandNode, though doing so =
would=20
be a fairly straightforward combination of XmlReader.ReadSubtree and=20
XmlDocument.Load.</P>
<P>I stuck the <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fcid-0d9bc809858885a4.skydrive.live.com%2fself.=
aspx%2fDevHawk%2520Content%2fIronPython%2520Stuff%2fipypulldom.py">code=20
for ipypulldom</A> up in a new folder on my Skydrive: <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fcid-0d9bc809858885a4.skydrive.live.com%2fbrows=
e.aspx%2fDevHawk%2520Content%2fIronPython%2520Stuff">IronPython=20
Stuff</A>. It's fairly short - only about 45 lines of code. Feel free to =
use it=20
if you need it.</P>
<HR>

<P>[1] The <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2ffepy.sourceforge.net%2f">FePy=20
project</A> has a <A=20
href=3D"http://devhawk.net/ct.ashx?id=3D381bc642-1227-46ac-8b2c-447db5ea9=
e7b&amp;url=3Dhttps%3a%2f%2ffepy.svn.sourceforge.net%2fsvnroot%2ffepy%2ft=
runk%2flib%2fpyexpat.py">.NET=20
port of pyexpat</A> as part of their distribution, so I assume that lets =
you use=20
the standard pulldom implementation in IPy. FePy looks really cool but I =
haven't=20
had time to dig into it yet. </P>
